TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Use of Knowledge for Technological Innovation Within Diversified Firms
AU  - Miller, Douglas J.
AU  - Fern, Michael J.
AU  - Cardinal, Laura B.
Y1  - 2007/04/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.24634437
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.24634437
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 307
EP  - 325
VL  - 50
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We propose that searching for and transferring knowledge across divisions in a diversified firm can cultivate innovation. Using a sample of 211,636 patents from 1,644 companies during the period 1985?1996, we find that the use of interdivisional knowledge positively affects the impact of an invention on subsequent technological developments. Furthermore, the positive effect of the use of interdivisional knowledge on the impact of an invention is stronger than the effect of using knowledge from within divisional boundaries or from outside firm boundaries. Our empirical findings have significant implications for the management of knowledge in diversified firms.
AB  - We propose that searching for and transferring knowledge across divisions in a diversified firm can cultivate innovation. Using a sample of 211,636 patents from 1,644 companies during the period 1985?1996, we find that the use of interdivisional knowledge positively affects the impact of an invention on subsequent technological developments. Furthermore, the positive effect of the use of interdivisional knowledge on the impact of an invention is stronger than the effect of using knowledge from within divisional boundaries or from outside firm boundaries. Our empirical findings have significant implications for the management of knowledge in diversified firms.
