TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is Public Ownership Bad for Professional Service Firms? Ad Agency Ownership, Performance, and Creativity
AU  - Von Nordenflycht, Andrew
Y1  - 2007/04/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.24634774
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.24634774
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 429
EP  - 445
VL  - 50
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Does public ownership create negative consequences for professional service firms by reducing employee incentives? This question was addressed with a panel of advertising agencies. Public ownership was associated with inferior performance for small agencies but not for large agencies, and there was no association between ownership and agency creativity, indicating that public ownership did not preclude agencies from competing with strategies requiring highly skilled professionals. The results challenge existing theories about the ownership of professional service firms.
AB  - Does public ownership create negative consequences for professional service firms by reducing employee incentives? This question was addressed with a panel of advertising agencies. Public ownership was associated with inferior performance for small agencies but not for large agencies, and there was no association between ownership and agency creativity, indicating that public ownership did not preclude agencies from competing with strategies requiring highly skilled professionals. The results challenge existing theories about the ownership of professional service firms.
